# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-efs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-efs/amazon-elastic-file-system] According to Amazon, use cases for this file system service typically include content repositories, development environments, web server farms, home directories and big data applications.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-elastic-file-system] Amazon EFS provides open-after-close consistency semantics that applications expect from NFS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-elastic-file-system] Amazon EFS is available in all the public AWS regions at least since December 2019.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-efs/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:aws-efs/high-availability] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A NAS device is optimised for serving files either by its hardware, software, or configuration.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] It is often manufactured as a computer appliance – a purpose-built specialized computer.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS systems are networked appliances that contain one or more storage drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Network-attached storage typically provide access to files using network file sharing protocols such as NFS, SMB, or AFP.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Accompanying a NAS are purpose-built hard disk drives, which are functionally similar to non-NAS drives but may have different firmware, vibration tolerance, or power dissipation to make them more suitable for use in RAID arrays, a technology often used in NAS implementations.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] For example, some NAS versions of drives support a command extension to allow extended error recovery to be disabled.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] In a non-RAID application, it may be important for a disk drive to go to great lengths to successfully read a problematic storage block, even if it takes several seconds.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] In an appropriately configured RAID array, a single bad block on a single drive can be recovered completely via the redundancy encoded across the RAID set.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A NAS unit is a computer connected to a network that provides only file-based data storage services to other devices on the network.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Although it may technically be possible to run other software on a NAS unit, it is usually not designed to be a general-purpose server.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] For example, NAS units usually do not have a keyboard or display, and are controlled and configured over the network, often using a browser.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A full-featured operating system is not needed on a NAS device, so often a stripped-down operating system is used.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS systems contain one or more hard disk drives, often arranged into logical, redundant storage containers or RAID.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS uses file-based protocols such as NFS (popular on UNIX systems), SMB (Server Message Block) (used with Microsoft Windows systems), AFP (used with Apple Macintosh computers), or NCP (used with OES and Novell NetWare).
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS units rarely limit clients to a single protocol.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The key difference between direct-attached storage (DAS) and NAS is that DAS is simply an extension to an existing server and is not necessarily networked.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] As the name suggests, DAS typically is connected via a USB or Thunderbolt enabled cable.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS is designed as an easy and self-contained solution for sharing files over the network.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Both DAS and NAS can potentially increase availability of data by using RAID or clustering.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Both NAS and DAS can have various amount of cache memory, which greatly affects performance.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] When comparing use of NAS with use of local (non-networked) DAS, the performance of NAS depends mainly on the speed of and congestion on the network.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Most NAS solutions will include the option to install a wide array of software applications to allow better configuration of the system or to include other capabilities outside of storage (like video surveillance, virtualization, media, etc).
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] DAS typically is focused solely on data storage but capabilities can be available based on specific vendor options.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS provides both storage and a file system.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] This is often contrasted with SAN (storage area network), which provides only block-based storage and leaves file system concerns on the "client" side.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] SAN protocols include Fibre Channel, iSCSI, ATA over Ethernet (AoE) and HyperSCSI.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Despite their differences, SAN and NAS are not mutually exclusive and may be combined as a SAN-NAS hybrid, offering both file-level protocols (NAS) and block-level protocols (SAN) from the same system.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A shared disk file system can also be run on top of a SAN to provide filesystem services.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] In the early 1980s, the "Newcastle Connection" by Brian Randell and his colleagues at Newcastle University demonstrated and developed remote file access across a set of UNIX machines.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Novell's NetWare server operating system and NCP protocol was released in 1983.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Following the Newcastle Connection, Sun Microsystems' 1984 release of NFS allowed network servers to share their storage space with networked clients.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] 3Com and Microsoft would develop the LAN Manager software and protocol to further this new market.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] 3Com's 3Server and 3+Share software was the first purpose-built server (including proprietary hardware, software, and multiple disks) for open systems servers.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Inspired by the success of file servers from Novell, IBM, and Sun, several firms developed dedicated file servers.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] While 3Com was among the first firms to build a dedicated NAS for desktop operating systems, Auspex Systems was one of the first to develop a dedicated NFS server for use in the UNIX market.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A group of Auspex engineers split away in the early 1990s to create the integrated NetApp FAS, which supported both the Windows SMB and the UNIX NFS protocols and had superior scalability and ease of deployment.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] This started the market for proprietary NAS devices now led by NetApp and EMC Celerra.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] In 2009, NAS vendors (notably CTERA networks and Netgear) began to introduce online backup solutions integrated in their NAS appliances, for online disaster recovery.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] By 2021, three major types of NAS solutions are offered (all with hybrid cloud models where data can be stored both on-premise on the NAS and off site on a separate NAS or through a public cloud service provider).
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The first type of NAS is focused on consumer needs with lower-cost options that typically support 1–5 hot plug hard drives.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The second is focused on small-to-medium-sized businesses – these NAS solutions range from 2–24+ hard drives and are typically offered in tower or rackmount form factors.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Pricing can vary greatly depending on the processor, components, and overall features supported.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The last type is geared toward enterprises or large businesses and are offered with more advanced software capabilities.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS solutions are typically sold without hard drives installed to allow the buyer (or IT departments) to select the hard drive cost, size, and quality.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Embedded-system-based NAS – using an ARM- or MIPS-based processor architecture and a real-time operating system (RTOS) or an embedded operating system to run a NAS server.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this NAS type is fair, and functions in the NAS can fit most end-user requirements.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Marvell, Oxford, and Storlink make chipsets for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Max FTP throughput varies from 20 MB/s to 120 MB/s.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] ASIC-based NAS – provisioning NAS through the use of a single ASIC chip, using hardware to implement TCP/IP and file system.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] There is no OS in the chip, as all the performance-related operations are done by hardware acceleration circuits.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The power consumption of this type of NAS is low, as functions are limited to only support SMB and FTP.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] LayerWalker is the only chipset manufacturer for this type of NAS.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS is useful for more than just general centralized storage provided to client computers in environments with large amounts of data.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] NAS can enable simpler and lower cost systems such as load-balancing and fault-tolerant email and web server systems by providing storage services.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] In the consumer market, NAS devices have evolved into "private cloud" solutions.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] They allow users to store multimedia data and back up files from various devices (such as smartphones and PCs) while retaining full data ownership.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Unlike public cloud services, these private cloud setups typically do not require monthly subscription fees for storage capacity.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Such consumer market appliances are now commonly available.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Unlike their rackmounted counterparts, they are generally packaged in smaller form factors.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The price of NAS appliances has fallen sharply in recent years, offering flexible network-based storage to the home consumer market for little more than the cost of a regular USB or FireWire external hard disk.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Many of these home consumer devices are built around ARM, x86 or MIPS processors running an embedded Linux operating system.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A **purpose-built backup appliance** (PBBA) is a kind of NAS intended for storing backup data.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] PBBAs typically include data deduplication, compression, RAID 6 or other redundant hardware components, and automated maintenance.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A PBBA may also be called a **backup and disaster recovery appliance** or simply a **backup appliance**.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Open-source NAS-oriented distributions of Linux and FreeBSD are available.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] These are designed to be easy to set up on commodity PC hardware, and are typically configured using a web browser.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] They can run from a virtual machine, Live CD, bootable USB flash drive (Live USB), or from one of the mounted hard drives.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] They run Samba (an SMB daemon), NFS daemon, and FTP daemons which are freely available for those operating systems.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] If the client can be granted access to the file requested, the client receives the network location of NASD disks and their capability.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] If the client is accessing the disk for the first time, it receives a time-limited key for the establishment of secure communication to the disk.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The file manager informs the corresponding disk using an independent channel.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] From now on, the client directly accesses the NASD disks by giving the capability it received and further data transfers go through the network, bypassing the file manager.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] A **clustered NAS** is a NAS that is using a distributed file system running simultaneously on multiple servers.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] The key difference between a clustered and traditional NAS is the ability to distribute (e.g. stripe) data and metadata across the cluster nodes or storage devices.
[src:aws-efs/network-attached-storage] Clustered NAS, like a traditional one, still provides unified access to the files from any of the cluster nodes, unrelated to the actual location of the data.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] A **clustered file system** (**CFS**) is a file system which is shared by being simultaneously mounted on multiple servers.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] There are several approaches to clustering, most of which do not employ a clustered file system (only direct attached storage for each node).
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Clustered file systems can provide features like location-independent addressing and redundancy which improve reliability or reduce the complexity of the other parts of the cluster.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] **Parallel file systems** are a type of clustered file system that spread data across multiple storage nodes, usually for redundancy or performance.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] A **shared-disk file system** uses a storage area network (SAN) to allow multiple computers to gain direct disk access at the block level.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Access control and translation from file-level operations that applications use to block-level operations used by the SAN must take place on the client node.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Shared-disk file-systems commonly employ some sort of fencing mechanism to prevent data corruption in case of node failures, because an unfenced device can cause data corruption if it loses communication with its sister nodes and tries to access the same information other nodes are accessing.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] The underlying storage area network may use any of a number of block-level protocols, including SCSI, iSCSI, HyperSCSI, ATA over Ethernet (AoE), Fibre Channel, network block device, and InfiniBand.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] There are different architectural approaches to a shared-disk filesystem.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Some distribute file information across all the servers in a cluster (fully distributed).
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Distributed data stores, by contrast, require using a different API or library and have different semantics (most often those of a database).
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Distributed file systems may aim for "transparency" in a number of aspects.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] That is, they aim to be "invisible" to client programs, which "see" a system which is similar to a local file system.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Behind the scenes, the distributed file system handles locating files, transporting data, and potentially providing other features listed below.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] The Incompatible Timesharing System used virtual devices for transparent inter-machine file system access in the 1960s.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] More file servers were developed in the 1970s.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] In 1976, Digital Equipment Corporation created the File Access Listener (FAL), an implementation of the Data Access Protocol as part of DECnet Phase II which became the first widely used network file system.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] In 1984, Sun Microsystems created the file system called "Network File System" (NFS) which became the first widely used Internet Protocol based network file system.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Other notable network file systems are Andrew File System (AFS), Apple Filing Protocol (AFP), NetWare Core Protocol (NCP), and Server Message Block (SMB) which is also known as Common Internet File System (CIFS).
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] In 1986, IBM announced client and server support for Distributed Data Management Architecture (DDM) for the System/36, System/38, and IBM mainframe computers running CICS.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] This was followed by the support for IBM Personal Computer, AS/400, IBM mainframe computers under the MVS and VSE operating systems, and FlexOS.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] DDM also became the foundation for Distributed Relational Database Architecture, also known as DRDA.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] There are many peer-to-peer network protocols for open-source distributed file systems for cloud or closed-source clustered file systems, e. g.: 9P, AFS, Coda, CIFS/SMB, DCE/DFS, WekaFS, Lustre, PanFS, Google File System, Mnet, Chord Project.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Network-attached storage (NAS) provides both storage and a file system, like a shared disk file system on top of a storage area network (SAN).
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] The failure of disk hardware or a given storage node in a cluster can create a single point of failure that can result in data loss or unavailability.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Fault tolerance and high availability can be provided through data replication of one sort or another, so that data remains intact and available despite the failure of any single piece of equipment.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] For examples, see the lists of distributed fault-tolerant file systems and distributed parallel fault-tolerant file systems.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] A common performance measurement of a clustered file system is the amount of time needed to satisfy service requests.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] In conventional systems, this time consists of a disk-access time and a small amount of CPU-processing time.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] But in a clustered file system, a remote access has additional overhead due to the distributed structure.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] This includes the time to deliver the request to a server, the time to deliver the response to the client, and for each direction, a CPU overhead of running the communication protocol software.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Concurrency control becomes an issue when more than one person or client is accessing the same file or block and want to update it.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] Hence updates to the file from one client should not interfere with access and updates from other clients.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] This problem is more complex with file systems due to concurrent overlapping writes, where different writers write to overlapping regions of the file concurrently.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] This problem is usually handled by concurrency control or locking which may either be built into the file system or provided by an add-on protocol.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] IBM mainframes in the 1970s could share physical disks and file systems if each machine had its own channel connection to the drives' control units.
[src:aws-efs/network-file-system] In the 1980s, Digital Equipment Corporation's TOPS-20 and OpenVMS clusters (VAX/ALPHA/IA64) included shared disk file systems.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In an economic context, a scalable business model implies that a company can increase sales given increased resources.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] For example, a package delivery system is scalable because more packages can be delivered by adding more delivery vehicles.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] However, if all packages had to first pass through a single warehouse for sorting, the system would not be as scalable, because one warehouse can handle only a limited number of packages.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In computing, scalability is a characteristic of computers, networks, algorithms, networking protocols, programs and applications.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] An example is a search engine, which must support increasing numbers of users, and the number of topics it indexes.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] **Webscale** is a computer architectural approach that brings the capabilities of large-scale cloud computing companies into enterprise data centers.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In distributed systems, there are several definitions according to the authors, some considering the concepts of scalability a sub-part of elasticity, others as being distinct.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but you need to consider total cost of ownership not just the infra cost.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In mathematics, scalability mostly refers to closure under scalar multiplication.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In industrial engineering and manufacturing, scalability refers to the capacity of a process, system, or organization to handle a growing workload, adapt to increasing demands, and maintain operational efficiency.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] A scalable system can effectively manage increased production volumes, new product lines, or expanding markets without compromising quality or performance.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In this context, scalability is a vital consideration for businesses aiming to meet customer expectations, remain competitive, and achieve sustainable growth.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Factors influencing scalability include the flexibility of the production process, the adaptability of the workforce, and the integration of advanced technologies.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] By implementing scalable solutions, companies can optimize resource utilization, reduce costs, and streamline their operations.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Scalability in industrial engineering and manufacturing enables businesses to respond to fluctuating market conditions, capitalize on emerging opportunities, and thrive in an ever-evolving global landscape.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] The Incident Command System (ICS) is used by emergency response agencies in the United States.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] ICS can scale resource coordination from a single-engine roadside brushfire to an interstate wildfire.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] The first resource on scene establishes command, with authority to order resources and delegate responsibility (managing five to seven officers, who will again delegate to up to seven, and on as the incident grows).
[src:aws-efs/scalability] As an incident expands, more senior officers assume command.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Resources fall into two broad categories: horizontal and vertical.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Scaling horizontally (out/in) means adding or removing nodes, such as adding a new computer to a distributed software application.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] An example might involve scaling out from one web server to three.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] High-performance computing applications, such as seismic analysis and biotechnology, scale workloads horizontally to support tasks that once would have required expensive supercomputers.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Other workloads, such as large social networks, exceed the capacity of the largest supercomputer and can only be handled by scalable systems.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Exploiting this scalability requires software for efficient resource management and maintenance.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Scaling vertically (up/down) means adding resources to (or removing resources from) a single node, typically involving the addition of CPUs, memory or storage to a single computer.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Benefits to scale-up include avoiding increased management complexity, more sophisticated programming to allocate tasks among resources and handling issues such as throughput, latency, and synchronization across nodes.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Moreover some applications do not scale horizontally.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Network function virtualization defines these terms differently: scaling out/in is the ability to scale by adding/removing resource instances (e.g., virtual machine), whereas scaling up/down is the ability to scale by changing allocated resources (e.g., memory/CPU/storage capacity).
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Scalability for databases requires that the database system be able to perform additional work given greater hardware resources, such as additional servers, processors, memory and storage.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Workloads have continued to grow and demands on databases have followed suit.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Algorithmic innovations include row-level locking and table and index partitioning.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Architectural innovations include shared-nothing and shared-everything architectures for managing multi-server configurations.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In the context of scale-out data storage, scalability is defined as the maximum storage cluster size which guarantees full data consistency, meaning there is only ever one valid version of stored data in the whole cluster, independently from the number of redundant physical data copies.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Clusters which provide "lazy" redundancy by updating copies in an asynchronous fashion are called 'eventually consistent'.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] This type of scale-out design is suitable when availability and responsiveness are rated higher than consistency, which is true for many web file-hosting services or web caches (*if you want the latest version, wait some seconds for it to propagate*).
[src:aws-efs/scalability] For all classical transaction-oriented applications, this design should be avoided.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Many open-source and even commercial scale-out storage clusters, especially those built on top of standard PC hardware and networks, provide eventual consistency only, such as some NoSQL databases like CouchDB and others mentioned above.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Write operations invalidate other copies, but often don't wait for their acknowledgements.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Read operations typically don't check every redundant copy prior to answering, potentially missing the preceding write operation.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] The large amount of metadata signal traffic would require specialized hardware and short distances to be handled with acceptable performance (i.e., act like a non-clustered storage device or database).
[src:aws-efs/scalability] It is often advised to focus system design on hardware scalability rather than on capacity.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] It is typically cheaper to add a new node to a system in order to achieve improved performance than to partake in performance tuning to improve the capacity that each node can handle.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] But this approach can have diminishing returns (as discussed in performance engineering).
[src:aws-efs/scalability] For example: suppose 70% of a program can be sped up if parallelized and run on multiple CPUs instead of one.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Doubling the processing power has only sped up the process by roughly one-fifth.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] If the whole problem was parallelizable, the speed would also double.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Therefore, throwing in more hardware is not necessarily the optimal approach.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] In distributed systems, you can use Universal Scalability Law (USL) to model and to optimize scalability of your system.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Gunther and quantifies scalability based on parameters such as contention and coherency.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Contention refers to delay due to waiting or queueing for shared resources.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Coherence refers to delay for data to become consistent.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] For example, having a high contention indicates sequential processing that could be parallelized, while having a high coherency suggests excessive dependencies among processes, prompting you to minimize interactions.
[src:aws-efs/scalability] Also, with help of USL, you can, in advance, calculate the maximum effective capacity of your system: scaling up your system beyond that point is a waste.
